4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA REQUESTING AN INTERIM STUDY OF COORDINATED HOMELESS SERVICES; AND
6 REQUIRING THAT THE FINAL RESULTS OF THE STUDY BE REPORTED TO THE 70TH LEGISLATURE.
7
8 WHEREAS, 9,352 Montanans needed shelter services in 2023; and
9 WHEREAS, 3,215 of those Montanans reported having at least one type of disabling condition; and
10 WHEREAS, stable housing results in better outcomes for individuals with physical disabilities, mental
11 health disorders, or substance abuse disorders; and
12 WHEREAS, between 2022 and 2024 the number of people in Montana seeking homeless services
13 increased by 10% and the number of chronically homeless people in Montana increased by 13.5%, according
14 to the Homeless Management Information System; and
15 WHEREAS, an evaluation conducted by the Montana Healthcare Foundation on permanent supportive
16 housing programs in Montana found a 48% reduction in detention center costs, a 3.8 times reduction in
17 emergency visits, and a 6.7 times reduction in total health costs after 6 months of being housed; and
18 WHEREAS, people who receive permanent supportive housing have a 98.12% retentional rate, which
19 was indicated by the percentage of people in permanent housing programs, excluding rapid rehousing
20 programs, retaining housing during the reporting year.
21
22 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
23 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
24 That the Legislative Council be requested to designate an appropriate interim committee or statutory
25 committee, pursuant to section 5-5-217, MCA, to conduct a meaningful and robust study on the benefits to the
26 state when homeless service providers are able to provide coordinated homeless services, including
27 wraparound services, and permanent supportive housing.
28 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the committee:
